15024 famous old Irish red setter wolfdog formerly known by the _sobriquet_ of
15025 Garryowen and recently rechristened by his large circle of friends and
15026 acquaintances Owen Garry. The exhibition, which is the result of years
15027 of training by kindness and a carefully thoughtout dietary system,
15028 comprises, among other achievements, the recitation of verse. Our
15029 greatest living phonetic expert (wild horses shall not drag it from us!)
15030 has left no stone unturned in his efforts to delucidate and compare
15031 the verse recited and has found it bears a _striking_ resemblance (the
15032 italics are ours) to the ranns of ancient Celtic bards. We are not
15033 speaking so much of those delightful lovesongs with which the writer who
15034 conceals his identity under the graceful pseudonym of the Little
15035 Sweet Branch has familiarised the bookloving world but rather (as
15036 a contributor D. O. C. points out in an interesting communication
15037 published by an evening contemporary) of the harsher and more personal
15038 note which is found in the satirical effusions of the famous Raftery and
15039 of Donal MacConsidine to say nothing of a more modern lyrist at present
15040 very much in the public eye. We subjoin a specimen which has been
15041 rendered into English by an eminent scholar whose name for the moment we
